This species is characterized by its generally slender habit with rather small elliptic leaves that have quite short petioles and domatia; its short, bilobed, hirtellous stipules; its rather short, congested cymose to subcapitate inflorescences; its small flowers with yellow corollas, and its small fruits that apparently become black at maturity. This species is not well characterized, and probably includes a heterogeneous group of plants in Bremekamp's circumscription; he included plants from variously an apparently humid habitat in the Manongarivo Massif in northern Madagscar, dry tsingy in western Madagascar, and humid forest in Analamazoatra in east-central Madagascar. Similar to his cirumscription plants are included here based on the diagnostic characters Bremekamp used to separate this species, but this will eventually need re-evaluation. Psychotria leilae is similar to Psychotria subcapitata, which has leaves without domatia and generally with rather bluntly angled apices, vs. sharp and weakly acuminate in Psychotria leilae.

January 2016.
Ranomafana, Madagascar.
One of the larger and more distinctive of the moths seen at our hotel near Ranomafana.
In addition to the moths there were several large mantises attracted to the lights.
The geckos of the building were having a great time thanks to the lights. This one is chewing on some kind of grasshopper/katydid.

We got to our hotel near Ranomafana too late in the day to do much birding, but after dark the hotel lights attracted a lot of amazing moths. This was probably the most dramatic of them, and it was also nice enough to perch on a plain black surface.
Ranomafana NP.
We saw two females of this species on our first day at Ranomafana, but unfortunately no males. The males are a brilliant velvety black and have bright green patches of bare skin above their eyes.
Another cool butterfly, this one from Ranomafana NP.
One of the less common Vanga species, found only in the eastern rainforest belt of Madagascar.
Seen on a hike in Ranomafana National Park... quite a curious little guy.
We took a night walk along the road at Ranomafana and found a lot of cool stuff. The most interesting were the chameleons in the trees by the roadside, but there was also this cool ring-necked snake.
On the same afternoon walk, we encountered several forest rats, which were searching for food on the forest floor and were remarkably approachable.

In the afternoon it was rainy, but we still went out for a walk to look for birds, and this lemur species, one of the rarest of them all.
It's confined to a small area in the eastern rainforests of Madagascar and wasn't discovered until the 1980s.
A cool frog with interesting "horns" above his eyes.

One very interesting thing about the chameleons is that they would turn darker once we shined a light on them. This one was green when we first saw it, but after just a minute or so of light it has turned mostly brown.
A chameleon blending into his surroundings with a mossy pattern.
The most beautiful chameleon we saw at Ranomafana was this small bright green one, clinging to the side of a leaf.
Some kind of geometer moth with quite a striking pattern.
Back at the hotel, there were again a lot of cool moths attracted to the lights.
At one place along the road there was some crushed fruit spread around to attract mouse lemurs. Later in the night we passed by it again and found a couple neat moths enjoying the free food.
At one place along the road there was some crushed fruit spread around to attract mouse lemurs. Later in the night we passed by it again and found a couple neat moths enjoying the free food.
The next morning I found this interesting sphinx moth species perched on the wall of the hotel. I've tentatively identified it as Maassenia heydeni.
One of the sifakas jumped from trunk to trunk several times, peeing in large quantities, presumably to mark these trees as their territory.
The Tylas Vanga is quite similar to the less common Pollen's Vanga, but has a thinner, all dark bill.
On our second morning in Ranomafana we encountered this species of Bamboo Lemur.
The weevil upon release back onto the bush it was found on. Our guide said this plant is where they are typically found.
Madagascar Buzzard observation here: http://www.inaturalist.org/observations/5057920
This was the best shot I got of this secretive understorey bird. We also saw the White-browed Oxylabes in the same area, but it was even less cooperative.
Drongo observation here: http://www.inaturalist.org/observations/5057915

From Ranomafana we drove north to spend the night in the city of Antsirabe.
Along the way we made a quick stop at a town with an egret colony.

Neotypification by way of one of these recent collections would greatly improve our ability to circumscribe the genus.

"More than 90 percent of the 103 species of lemurs in Madagascar are in severe danger of disappearing from this Earth forever. Why the crisis?  Since a political coup in 2009, laws are not being enforced and illegal logging, fires to turn forests into charcoal and hunting of lemurs is rampant throughout much of Madagascar."
https://www.huffpost.com/entry/madagascar-lemurs_b_1684471 

My travel from Canada to Madagascar generated an estimated environmental impact of 6,3 tons of CO2. Instead of “compensating” this negative effect by paying 280$ CAN in this case, I prefer to have a direct positive effect on the countries that I visit. For this particular trip, I donated 215$ US to the rainforest conservation fund of Stony Brook University, to support activities of the ValBio center (https://www.stonybrook.edu/commcms/centre-valbio/index.html). 

"Centre ValBio works to protect Madagascar’s unique and biologically diverse ecosystems through conservation science and projects that directly benefit the local people, including rural health care delivery. CVB has a world-class research station sited on the edge of Madagascar's beautiful and abundant Ranomafana National Park. Under the direction of world-renowned primatologist Patricia Wright, Centre ValBio facilitates hands-on science to sustain the resources and people of Madagascar. In collaboration with villagers, we're expanding the frontiers of knowledge while safeguarding biodiversity for future generations."

Consider supporting the ValBio center if you visit this country and more especially, Ranomafana National Park: https://www.stonybrook.edu/commcms/centre-valbio/giving.html

"More than 90 percent of the 103 species of lemurs in Madagascar are in severe danger of disappearing from this Earth forever. Why the crisis? Since a political coup in 2009, laws are not being enforced and illegal logging, fires to turn forests into charcoal and hunting of lemurs is rampant throughout much of Madagascar."
https://www.huffpost.com/entry/madagascar-lemurs_b_1684471

My travel from Canada to Madagascar generated an estimated environmental impact of 6,3 tons of CO2. Instead of “compensating” this negative effect by paying 280$ CAN in this case, I prefer to have a direct positive effect on the countries that I visit. For this particular trip, I donated 215$ US to the rainforest conservation fund of Stony Brook University, to support activities of the ValBio center (https://www.stonybrook.edu/commcms/centre-valbio/index.html).

"Centre ValBio works to protect Madagascar’s unique and biologically diverse ecosystems through conservation science and projects that directly benefit the local people, including rural health care delivery. CVB has a world-class research station sited on the edge of Madagascar's beautiful and abundant Ranomafana National Park. Under the direction of world-renowned primatologist Patricia Wright, Centre ValBio facilitates hands-on science to sustain the resources and people of Madagascar. In collaboration with villagers, we're expanding the frontiers of knowledge while safeguarding biodiversity for future generations."

Consider supporting the ValBio center if you visit this country and more especially, Ranomafana National Park: https://www.stonybrook.edu/commcms/centre-valbio/giving.html
